i found a nest with one egg on my balcony now what i diddnt see a mama wow i hate how you cant reply so theres different nests on my balcony one ive known about for about weeks now which is up high and mama pigeon there today i find a nd nest in the corner with a single egg dunno if its a pigeon or not but its just there no bird has come to check on it in the past uh or hours since ive discovered it step away from the nest if the mother bird sees you she will not return if the egg is not viable if the embryo is dead she will probably not return if something has happened to her she may not be able to return unfortunately you may not do anything to try to save the egg in the us it is illegal to take an egg out of a wild bird's nest as stated on http www npwrc usgs gov about faqs birds feathers htm anyone desiring to possess migratory birds or their parts or products should be aware that all of these are covered under the migratory bird treaty act u s c which implements a series of international treaties designed to protect migratory birds some key provisions of the act are worth keeping in mind wording of the act makes it very clear that most actions that result in taking or possession of a protected species or its parts or products is a violation of the act specifically the act states unless and except as permitted by regulations it shall be unlawful at any time by any means or in any manner to pursue hunt take capture kill possess offer for sale sell purchase import any migratory bird any part nest or eggs of any such bird it is a strict liability law meaning that there is no requirement for law enforcement agencies to prove intent to violate the law that is if you are found in possession of a protected species or its parts or products you are automatically in violation of the law the provisions of the act are nearly absolute except as permitted by regulations is the only exception some examples of permitted activities that do not violate the law are legal hunting of specific game birds legitimate research activities display in licensed zoological gardens and bird banding under an appropriate permit the act covers the great majority of all native birds found in the u s many of the species not covered by the act are covered by the endangered species act other federal laws or state laws many of which are as stringent as the migratory bird treaty act in the lower states all species except the house sparrow feral pigeon common starling and non migratory game birds like pheasants gray partridge and sage grouse are protected penalties upon conviction can be severe even if a sympathetic jury finds that you meant no harm in trying to rear an abandoned nestling or in picking a hawk feather legal defense costs are clearly not worth the risk many other countries have similar laws to protect their native migratory birds Constitution of the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus Bird Single Convention on Narcotic Drugs Freedom of speech Hunting Migratory Bird Treaty Act of 1918 Trademark Treaty Introduced species Plame affair Contract Falconry Appeal Law Intellectual property Child pornography Gun politics in the United States Cannabis rescheduling in the United States Gun politics Constitution of Ireland Due process Copyright House Sparrow First Amendment to the United States Constitution Digital rights management Kakapo Slander and libel Conspiracy Capercaillie Endangered Species Act Convention on Psychotropic Substances Microeconomics Country parks and conservation in Hong Kong Fair use Food and Drug Administration United States Constitution Australian constitutional law Environmental Protection Agency Classified information Online Copyright Infringement Liability Limitation Act Peregrine Falcon Albatross Bird migration Capitalism Public domain Estoppel International Criminal Court Copyright law of the United Kingdom Treaty establishing a Constitution for Europe Theory of conduct USA PATRIOT Act Equal Protection Clause Juris Doctor Fox hun